> >Btw - have u tried to (during playing WOut) switch with Amiga+M to WB and
> then go back to play screen. What happens to you? Here all textures got 
> "errors" on them...
> Another good example how MESSY the integration of Warp3D into the system
> really is. There is absolutely no way to allocate texture memory which
> is guaranteed to stay at the same location forever. Warp3D uses bitmaps
> for texture storage and bitmaps are moved around by the RTG system,
> if other bitmaps are put into VRAM (and this happens very likely when
> screens are switched). If this happens, then the bitmaps end up somewhere
> else while Warp3D still uses the data at the old location.

There are two approaches, I know of:

1) provide callbacks in the driver where the application can hook into and
   get notified when "things change".
2) have the driver maintain the textures and other vital data in host-memory
   and automagically cache textures into the card's memory. However the
   drivrs needs to be notified of "things changing" by the RTG system as well.

I ran into a very similar problem on the Mac when the user (or application)
changed the screenmode (resolution changes availabe memory) or colordepth
(accelerate at all? memory? changed byteorder which affects packetwriting
into the command FIFO...).

My solution was a combination of both, I provide callback hooks for the
application and my driver gets notified by the ROM (2D drvier) when things
change.

By the way, assuming I have multiple Warp3D contexts spread over multiple
screens, are the contexts on currently invisible (not being the frontmost)
screens expected to continue rendering, to stop rendering or is the expected
behaviour not defined?

On combined 2D/3D cards this is less a problem than on special solutions
like the ParaGlide is to become, because the feeding of rendered 3D data
into the 2D chip is done through capturing and the capture bus has to be
arbitrated between FlickerFixer, Paloma and ParaGlide. 
This arbitration currently works (and most probabaly will remain so) 
through an "active context" which is the last one (most often on the now 
front screen) that got activated. 
Activating one context disables all others that may be present...

