>> It depends on the target bitmap, if it's in VRAM, then rendering
>> takes place, even if the bitmap isn't visible (that's because rendering
>> to hidden buffers is perfectly legal and common for multibuffered
>> applications). If it's in FAST-RAM, then the actual drawing isn't done
>> (in fact, if it's not in VRAM, then W3D_LockHardware should return
>> with an error and the application should enter a paused mode).

>I see. So when I want a specific context not to render, I just let
>W3D_LockHardware fail and this is perfectly legal?

Probably the cleanest solution, as a failed Lockhardware call implies
that the hardware currently isn't available, and application should
take care of this. But beware, you must still check the locking state
inside the rendering functions, most applications probably ignore
the error code of LockHardware, so you should immediately return,
if someone wants to draw a primitive outside locked state.

You should check, whether there is a suitable error code for
LockHardware, which fits to what you need. If not, then we will
introduce a new one for V3. In general you should report to us,
if you need something special, as a V3 release is not too far
away anymore.

>What about W3D_INDIRECT, is it legal to only implement indirect mode
>or is direct mode mandatory at the driver level.

Indirect/direct contexts work outside the driver in the main lib, so
you don't have to deal with it.

>Same question for W3D_AUTOTEXMANAGEMENT, is manual texture management 
>mandatory or can I get by with only automagic management?

It's a bit critical to fake manual texture management this way, because
application might be smarter than the automatic texture management,
because it knows about application behaviour. So it's more a performance
question rather than a functionality question. A uploaded texture
simply must be available if a primitive with that texture is drawn
and it should be available directly resp. be in VRAM, because
application expects this to happen and optimizes its algorithms
according to this behaviour.

bye
