About the same speed. And I guess I know why. There are different limiting
factors with Quake. 

For one, it doesn't optimize the way textures are handled, from my quick
peeks at the source code, I would say it binds textures as soon as it
needs them, so there may be texture swaps even during the frame drawing.

Then, Quake has the inherent problem that it was designed with software
rendering in mind. The GL version is really a bit of a hack. The way it
works now, you'll end up with a lot of overdraw, which is a killer for the
Permedia. Quake 2 got rid of some of the overdraw by introducing
visibility portals, which are basically "doorways" between regions of the
level. When a doorway isn't visible, you don't draw anything that's behind
that.  That's why Heretic 2 is actually faster than Quake, even though the
geometry is more complex. It just doesn't draw everything that could
potentially be seen.

I think there's a r_draworder that can reverse the drawing order of
polygons in Quake. Set it to 1 (or 0), and see what is really "visible"...

