> Does not sound like it can be fixed? Means this I can forget about
> playing GL-Quake, HereticII, Shogo and so on with my A4000 and
> Cybervision64-3D?

Yes and No. 

The Problem *can* be fixed, in fact, Heretic II showed the same graphics
bug in the beginning, and I added a small fix into MiniGL. Normally you
would use the call glPolygonOffset for this, but that didn't fit too well,
so I added a function

mglSetZOffset(GLfloat offset);

which introduces the offset to be added, and a state MGL_Z_OFFSET that can
be enabled and disabled with glEnable/glDisable. Massimiliano would have
to add a new console variable (in Heretic II I called it gl_polyoffset)
which the user can set to a very small value (like 0.0001), and GLQuake
should glEnable(MGL_Z_OFFSET) before drawing a lightmap, and glDisable
afterwards. 

So much for the good news. Now for the bad news.

Forget about playing Heretic II and Shogo on the CV64/3D. The ViRGE chip
cannot handle this. The software renderer for H2 will be faster for a fast
PPC (like 604/200). 

Shogo might be playable, since it has an option for switching off
lightmaps and use vertex lighting instead, which essentially means you
only need half the fill rate. 

I found that even on my overclocked 060/66, the software renderer is
slightly faster...

> Any new powerfull 3D-Graphicscards (cheaper than 200 Euro) in sight?

