Hehe, just overdrawing the scene... in fact every pixel that is rendered
more than one time is overdraw... (!?) the permedia seems to be constructed
to perform 640x480 or 800x600 graphics with average fps when every pixel is
set just once, but most of today's engines have much more overdraw (quake
for e.g. draws nearly every poly twice as it renderes the whole
lightmap-thingy in a second pass... and every transparent surface has to be
rendered over other surfaces, so every watereffect in an engine causes more
overdraw..)

this leds me to another interesting effect the beginners of 3d-coding should
keep in mind... the z-buffer test is performed as one of the first
operations (and one of the fastest ;) in the rendering pipe of 3d-hardware,
so u could save much time (overdraw) by processing the scene in front to
back order (i.e. render the enemy's & items first and then the background
from front to back..) This means the pixels in the foreground wich were
once set are finished and will not cause any further overdraw (just some
relativly quick z-tests..) ... Just for the once who didn't knew (like me
in my hw-accelerated beginning-day's..;)..

