Schulze_Michael@t-online.de (Michael Schulze) wrote:
>What exactly is meant with "overdraw" ? You know, this feature, what the
>Permedia2 lacks of... ;)

"overdraw" is simply drawing over the top of something drawn earlier
in the same frame.  For example, the classic "painters" algorithm for
3D scenes starts by drawing the most distant background first, then
drawing foreground objects over the top, sorted by distance.

Better 3D algorithms have less overdraw, or none at all.  If a 3D card
has a very fast pixel fill rate, then overdraw doesn't matter so much.
I think the point being made about Permedia2 is that its pixel fill
rate is relatively slow --- that is, compared to the latest 3D cards
for PCs.  And since GLQuake does a lot of overdraw, the Permedia2 is
penalised for this.

BTW, as far as I can see, there is no overdraw in ordinary Quake for:
walls; ceilings; floors and static objects.  The only overdraw is for:
enemies; rotating objects (armour/weapons); weapon trails;
explosions; console blind and text.  On the other hand, GLQuake
probably uses different algorithms altogether...
